Mohammad Anas Rehman

Published

Introduction

Imagine being born in a country where your chances of surviving past your fifth birthday are 10 times lower than someone else’s — simply because of where you were born.
This is the reality for millions of young girls globally. This report analyzes under-five female mortality using UNICEF datasets, highlighting not just the numbers, but the human stories behind them.

Mortality Trends Over Time (Time Series)

While many countries have made impressive gains since 2000, progress has been uneven.
Countries like India and Bangladesh show encouraging improvements, reflecting the impact of sustained public health campaigns.
However, in countries like Nigeria, gains have been far more modest — a signal that interventions are not reaching everyone equally.

Code 
import polars as pl
import pandas as pd
from plotnine import *
import geopandas as gpd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

indicator = pl.read_csv("unicef_indicator_1.csv")
metadata = pl.read_csv("unicef_metadata.csv", infer_schema_length=10000, ignore_errors=True)


under5_female = (
    indicator
    .filter(
        (pl.col("indicator") == "Under-five deaths") &
        (pl.col("sex") == "Female") &
        (pl.col("time_period") >= 2000)
    )
    .select([
        pl.col("country"),
        pl.col("alpha_3_code"),
        pl.col("time_period").alias("year"),
        pl.col("obs_value").alias("under_five_deaths")
    ])
)


selected_countries = ["India", "Nigeria", "Pakistan", "Ethiopia", "Bangladesh"]

under5_female_selected = (
    under5_female
    .filter(pl.col("country").is_in(selected_countries))
    .sort(["country", "year"])
)

df_ts = under5_female_selected.to_pandas()

final_year = df_ts["year"].max()
df_ts["label"] = df_ts.apply(lambda row: row["country"] if row["year"] == final_year else "", axis=1)

(
    ggplot(df_ts) +
    aes(x="year", y="under_five_deaths", color="country", group="country") +
    geom_line(size=1.5) +
    geom_point(size=2.5) +
    geom_text(aes(label="label"), ha="left", nudge_x=0.2, size=9) +
    theme_minimal() +
    scale_color_brewer(type="qual", palette="Dark2") +
    labs(
        title="Sharp Declines in Female Under-5 Deaths — But Uneven Progress",
        x="Year",
        y="Number of Deaths",
        color="Country"
    )
)

Top 10 Countries in 2020 (Bar Chart)

This chart answers a critical question: where is the problem the worst right now?
A few countries account for a disproportionately high number of under-five deaths — and tackling the crisis in these areas is essential for moving the global average.

Code 
under5_2020 = (
    under5_female
    .filter(pl.col("year") == 2020)
    .sort("under_five_deaths", descending=True)
    .head(10)
)
df_bar = under5_2020.to_pandas()

(
    ggplot(df_bar) +
    aes(x="reorder(country, under_five_deaths)", y="under_five_deaths", fill="country") +
    geom_col(show_legend=False) +
    geom_text(aes(label="under_five_deaths"), nudge_y=1000, size=8, format_string="{:,.0f}") +
    coord_flip() +
    scale_fill_brewer(type="qual", palette="Set3") +
    theme_minimal() +
    labs(
        title="Top 10 Countries by Female\n Under-5 Deaths 2020",
        x="Country",
        y="Number of Deaths"
    )
)

GDP vs Child Mortality (Scatterplot)

Does being a richer country mean fewer child deaths? Generally, yes.
But this chart also shows exceptions — middle-income countries with surprisingly high mortality, and poorer nations that outperform expectations.
These outliers show the importance of health systems, governance, and education, not just GDP.

Code 
joined = (
    under5_female
    .join(metadata, on=["country", "year"], how="left")
    .filter(pl.col("year") == 2020)
    .select([
        pl.col("country"),
        pl.col("under_five_deaths"),
        pl.col("GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)").alias("gdp_per_capita")
    ])
    .drop_nulls()
)
df_scatter = joined.to_pandas()

# Identify top 5 countries by death count for labeling
top_countries = df_scatter.nlargest(5, "under_five_deaths")["country"].tolist()
df_scatter["label"] = df_scatter["country"].apply(lambda x: x if x in top_countries else None)


(
    ggplot(df_scatter) +
    aes(x="gdp_per_capita", y="under_five_deaths") +
    geom_point(color="#2c7fb8", size=2) +
    geom_text(aes(label="label"), na_rm=True, nudge_y=10000, size=8, ha="left") +
    geom_smooth(method="lm", color="red", se=True) +
    scale_x_log10() +
    theme_minimal() +
    labs(
        title="GDP vs Female Under-5 Deaths (2020)",
        x="GDP per Capita (log scale)",
        y="Under-5 Female Deaths"
    )
)

Global Distribution (2020) World Map

This map is more than data. It’s a visual wake-up call.
It reveals the stark inequality that persists across regions, with Sub-Saharan Africa and parts of South Asia still facing the highest burden.
Where a girl is born shouldn’t determine whether she survives.

Code 
import geopandas as gpd

# Load world boundaries
shape_world = gpd.read_file("https://public.opendatasoft.com/api/explore/v2.1/catalog/datasets/world-administrative-boundaries/exports/shp")



# Used 3-letter country codes for easier merging
under5_map_data = (
    under5_female
    .filter(pl.col("year") == 2020)
    .select(["alpha_3_code", "under_five_deaths"])
    .drop_nulls()
    .to_pandas()
)

map_merged = shape_world.merge(
    under5_map_data,
    left_on="iso3",
    right_on="alpha_3_code",
    how="left"
)

(
    ggplot(map_merged) +
    aes(map_id="iso3", fill="under_five_deaths") +
    geom_map() +
    coord_fixed() +
    scale_fill_gradient(low="lightyellow", high="darkred") +
    theme_minimal() +
    labs(
        title="Global Distribution of Female Under-5 Deaths (2020)",
        fill="Deaths",
        caption="Grey indicates missing data"
    )
)

Conclusion

The story these numbers tell is clear: progress has been made — but we’re not done.
Every chart here represents not just data points, but lives.
Data like this should inform not only dashboards — but decisions.

The tools exist. The knowledge exists. What remains is urgency.
